{
  "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema",
  "$id": "https://example.org/schema.json",
  "title": "User Registration Form Schema",
  "type": "object",
  "required": ["username", "email", "password"],
  "properties": {
    "username": {
      "type": "string",
      "minLength": 3,
      "maxLength": 20,
      "pattern": "^[a-zA-Z]{3,20}$"
    },
    "email": {
      "type": "string",
      "format": "email"
    },
    "password": {
      "type": "string",
      "minLength": 8,
      "maxLength": 20
    }
  },
  "additionalProperties": false,
  "examples": [
    {
      "username": "John Doe",
      "email": "johndoe@example.com",
      "password": "123456"
    },
    {
      "username": "Jane Doe",
      "email": "janedoe@example.com",
      "password": "123456"
    }
  ]
}
```

Explanation:

- `$schema` is the schema URL, which is the location of this schema in JSON.
- `title` is the name of the schema, which is "User Registration Form Schema" for this schema.
- `type` is the type of the JSON object, which is "object" for this schema.
- `required` is an array of required fields, which is `[username, email, password]` for this schema.
- `properties` is an object with nested properties, which is `{ "username": { ... }, "email": { ... }, "password": { ... } }` for this schema.
- `additionalProperties` is false, which means that there cannot be additional properties.
- `examples` is a list of objects, each with a unique `username`, `email`, and `password`.

This schema validates that the user registration form contains required fields, as well as types, minLength, maxLength, and pattern constraints. It also validates that the `username`, `email`, and `password` properties are of the expected types. The nested `properties` object validates that there are nested properties for each of these fields, and that each nested property has the same type as the corresponding nested property. The `additionalProperties` property is set to false to ensure that there are no additional properties.

